1. Frontier Detection and Clustering (12 points)\
Replace the random frontier detector with a proper implementation. A frontier cell is a free cell that has\
at least one unknown 4-neighbor (up, down, left, right). Your implementation should:\
\'95 Scan the occupancy grid and identify all frontier cells.\
\'95 Cluster frontier cells into contiguous frontier regions using BFS (flood-fill) with 4-connectivity. Each\
cluster represents a connected segment of the exploration boundary.\
\'95 Filter out regions with fewer than 
\f1 FRONTIER_MIN_SIZE 
\f0 cells (defined in 
\f1 config.py
\f0 , default 3).\
These tiny clusters are noise and should be discarded.\
\'95 Return a list of 
\f1 FrontierRegion 
\f0 objects, each containing the cluster cells, centroid, and size.\
Use the function template 
\f1 detect_frontiers() 
\f0 in 
\f1 exploration.py
\f0 . Guidance comments and a\
scaffolded structure are provided in the file.\
2. Goal Selection Strategies (16 points total)\
Implement two goal selection strategies to replace the random baseline.\
Part 2a: Nearest Frontier (10 points) \'97 Select the closest reachable frontier cell by path cost. For\
each frontier region whose centroid is not blacklisted, plan a path from the robot\'92s current position to\
the centroid and choose the goal with the minimum path cost. If a centroid falls on a non-free cell\
(e.g., a wall), snap it to the nearest free cell. Use the function template 
\f1 select_goal_nearest()\

\f0 in 
\f1 exploration.py
\f0 .\
